Halve, peel and chop the @red onion{1}(halved and chopped) into small pieces. Peel and grate
the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Chop the
@potatoes{450%g}(cut into 2cm chunks) (no need to peel!) Roughly chop the
@coriander{1/2%bunch}(chopped) (stalks and all). Halve the
@lime{1/2}(halved). Heat a splash of @oil{} in a large #saucepan{} on medium
heat. When hot, add the onion and cook, stirring frequently until soft,
~{5-6%minutes}. Add the garlic and cook for ~{1%minute} more. Take out half of
this mixture, set aside in a #bowl{}.

Meanwhile, put the @British beef mince{240%g} in a bowl, season with a pinch of
@salt{} and @pepper{}. Add half the coriander and mix together. Shape the
mixture into four balls per person. IMPORTANT: Remember to wash your hands after
handling raw meat! Heat a splash of oil in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat
and fry the koftas until golden brown all over, ~{5-6%minutes}, turning
occasionally.

While the koftas are frying, add the @ground cumin{2%tsp}, @ground turmeric{1%tsp}
and @mustard seeds{1%tsp} to the saucepan with the onion and cook, stirring,
for ~{30%seconds}. Add the potatoes, @water for the potatoes{150%ml} and half
the @chicken stock paste{1/2%tbsp}. Bring to the boil, stirring to dissolve the
stock powder. Cover with a #lid{}, turn the heat to low and simmer, stirring
occasionally, until the potato is just cooked, ~{15-20%minutes}. Tip: The potato
is cooked when you can easily slip a knife through.

Take the koftas out of the pan and set aside. Add the reserved onion mix to the
same pan (no need to wash!) along with the @rogan josh curry paste{50%g} and
@tomato puree{30%g}. Stir together and cook on medium-low heat for
~{30%seconds} before adding the @coconut milk{400%ml} with @water for the curry{150%ml}.
Stir in the remaining stock powder and a pinch of @?sugar{}, add the koftas and
cover with a lid (or some #foil{}) and simmer for ~{8-10%minutes}. Remove the
lid and simmer for another ~{3-4%minutes}. You want the sauce to reduce slightly.
IMPORTANT: The koftas are cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

When the potato is cooked, remove the lid and allow the mixture to bubble away
for a few minutes more, until the liquid has almost gone, stirring frequently
to ensure it doesn't burn. Add the @baby spinach{125%g} a handful at a time,
carefully stirring through the potatoes until wilted, ~{2-3%minutes}. This is
your sag aloo!

When the kofta curry has reduced slightly, squeeze in a little lime juice and
stir through. Serve the beef kofta curry sprinkled with the remaining coriander
and the sag aloo on the side. Enjoy!

> For many people, rice is often the go-to side for a curry. We've decided to
> serve our aromatic beef kofta curry alongside sag aloo, a nutritious dish of
> spinach, potato and fragrant spices, which gives rice a serious run for its
> money. Easy to prep, and even easier to eat, this is a curry you'll be coming
> back to time and time again.